    <!-- SCIENCE SECTION -->
    <h2 id="science">The Science Behind Fadogia Agrestis: An Honest Assessment</h2>

    <p>Transparency demands that we address the evidence gap directly: fadogia agrestis is the most popular supplement ingredient in America that has never been tested in a single published human clinical trial. Everything we know about its effects on testosterone comes from one animal study, and that same study raised safety concerns. Here is what the research actually shows:</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>The 2005 study in the <em>Asian Journal of Andrology</em> administered fadogia agrestis stem extract to male Wistar rats at three doses — 18mg/kg, 50mg/kg, and 100mg/kg body weight — for 5 days. Testosterone increased <strong>dose-dependently</strong> at all three levels. However, at the highest dose (100mg/kg), researchers observed <strong>significant changes in testicular histology</strong> and increased testicular weight that suggested potential organ toxicity.</p>
      <cite>Yakubu et al., Asian Journal of Andrology, 2005</cite>
    </div>

    <div class="vs-strip">
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Fadogia Agrestis Evidence</strong>
        <p>1 animal study (2005)<br />0 human clinical trials<br />Dose-dependent testicular concerns in rats</p>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Tongkat Ali Evidence</strong>
        <p>9+ randomized controlled trials<br />2022 meta-analysis confirming efficacy<br />12-week safety data in humans</p>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Ashwagandha Evidence</strong>
        <p>15+ randomized controlled trials<br />KSM-66: 24 clinical studies<br />Extensive long-term safety data</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Critical safety guidance:</strong> If you choose to supplement with fadogia agrestis despite the limited evidence, follow these precautions: (1) Use conservative cycling — 5 days on, 2 days off or 8 weeks on, 4 weeks off. (2) Get baseline bloodwork before starting and retest at 8 weeks, including testosterone, LH, FSH, liver enzymes, and kidney markers. (3) Do not exceed 600mg daily. (4) Discontinue immediately if you experience testicular pain, significant mood changes, or other unexpected symptoms.</p>
    </div>

