    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Fadogia Agrestis Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is fadogia agrestis and why is it trending?</summary>
      <p>Fadogia agrestis is a West African shrub whose stem has been used in Nigerian traditional medicine as an aphrodisiac. It gained mainstream attention after neuroscientist Andrew Huberman discussed it as part of a natural testosterone optimization protocol alongside tongkat ali. Google searches have increased over 1,200% since 2023, though the ingredient has no published human clinical trials.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does fadogia agrestis actually increase testosterone?</summary>
      <p>The evidence is limited to a single 2005 animal study in the <em>Asian Journal of Andrology</em> that found dose-dependent testosterone increases in rats. The mechanism involves LH stimulation. No human clinical trials have been published, making the evidence significantly weaker than for tongkat ali, ashwagandha, or maca.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is fadogia agrestis safe?</summary>
      <p>Safety data is limited. The same animal study that showed testosterone increases also observed testicular histology changes at higher doses. Without human safety data, long-term effects are unknown. Conservative dosing (fewer than 600mg daily), cycling protocols, and regular bloodwork monitoring are recommended.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the Huberman fadogia agrestis protocol?</summary>
      <p>Andrew Huberman has discussed 600mg fadogia agrestis daily, paired with 400mg tongkat ali, with cycling breaks and regular bloodwork monitoring. This protocol is based on extrapolation from animal research and personal experience, not published human clinical trials.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take fadogia agrestis with tongkat ali?</summary>
      <p>The combination is popular but has never been studied in a controlled trial. The theoretical rationale is that fadogia stimulates LH while tongkat ali reduces SHBG. Tongkat ali alone has substantially more clinical evidence, so risk-averse consumers may prefer it as a standalone option.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does it take for fadogia agrestis to work?</summary>
      <p>In rats, testosterone increases appeared within 5 days. Human timelines are unknown. Anecdotal reports suggest one to three weeks for energy and libido effects. If combining with tongkat ali, the tongkat ali effects (supported by human data) typically appear at four to six weeks.</p>
    </details>

